23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?

    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}

    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}

        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}

    body: JSON.stringify({ code })
  }

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}
Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?

    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}

23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

  }

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}
Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?

Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}

interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}

This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”

4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}
Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?

23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?

OCT - 11 ( Building a Video chat Application )

1. WebSockets
2. WebRtc
3. Signaling
4. SDP and ICE Candidates
5. Agora

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}
Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?

    }

23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9
-----------

2. async function() and awsit in JS

 const res = await fetch('/run', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ code })
  }
3. What is a browser API ?  Use of '/run' and What happens when you call '/run' ?
4. Why i have to make HTTP request ? 
5. What is header ? what is the need to use it ? 
6. What is a js Object? 
7. What is a promise ?
8. What is JSON ans javascript object ?

const express = require('express'); 
const bodyParser = require('body-parser'); 
const fs = require('fs'); 
const { exec } = require('child_process'); 
const path = require('path');
9. What is Express ? Its use here.
10. What is bodyParser ? Its use here.
11. Use of fs, exec, paths here

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}
Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }

This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”

2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?

3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?

Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?

7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?

            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }

class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}
Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}

23. How come local records be static ?ow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. The exact installation procedure depends on your machine and operating system but the most common way would be to use pip. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can alsoow to Install Ansible To start using Ansible, you will need to install it on a control node, this could be your laptop for example. From this control node, Ansible will connect and manage other machines and orchestrate different tasks. Installation Requirements Your control node can be any machine with Python 3.8 or newer, but Windows is not supported. For the managed nodes, Ansible needs to communicate with them over SSH and SFTP (this can also be switched to SCP via the ansible.cfg file) or WinRM for Windows hosts. The managed nodes also need Python 2 (version 2.6 or later) or Python (version 3.5 or later) and in the case of Windows nodes PowerShell 3.0 or later and at least .NET 4.0 installed. To install pip, in case it’s not already available on your system: After pip is installed: $ python -m pip install --user ansible Since there are different ways to install it for every operating system you can also
Configuration Management: — Configuration management (CM) refers to the process of
systematically handling changes to a system in a way that maintains integrity over time.
Ansible is a configuration management tool and automation engine that automates software
provisioning and application deployment.
 Manages Infrastructure whether it is on-premises or cloud.
 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?

    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}

 We are going to tell the state of a machine and Ansible will maintain the state is always
available.

 Ansible will do convergence which means if you tell Ansible to make sure java-1.8 is available
and Jenkins is running in a machine, ansible will check and if Java is already available it only
installs Jenkins and makes sure Jenkins is always running.
 We can use ansible for deployment which means we can use ansible to call container or to call
Kubernetes.OCT - 9

1. WebSockets

 We define the state of our machine in yaml file.
 Before Ansible there were several CM tools like Puppet and Chef that needed agent software.
 Ansible is agentless. It works on SSH and Python, Internally ansible is a Python script.
 You cannot install Ansible on Windows, you will be installing Ansible in Linux but using
Ansible you can connect to a Windows or Linux machine and do configuration management.

Setup Ansible on Aws (Ubuntu server):-
 Launch an instance from aws launch wizard.
 Make sure SSH port 22 is available on securitygroup.
 Name your server as ‘Ansible_Master’ and connect to that machine.
 Update packages by running below command.1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
2. I can't able to access a public method from a non-public class (one package) in my class (another package) but jvm (it is also a program with a call to main() in it) able to access my main() even my class is not public. How ?
package com1.package1;
public class Demo1{
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("IM from pack 1");
    }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
package com2.pack2;
import com1.package1.Demo1;
class Demo2{
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo1 d = new Demo1();
        d.m1();
    }
}

If Demo1 is not public i'm unable to use m1() in Demo2 even after importing, because the class is not public. But even though I didn't make my class as public how JVM is calling my main() from my non-public class ?
------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Why java still not implemented multiple inheritance ?
4. Can I add heterogenous Objects to TreeSet ? Yes, is we use CSO
5. Can I add null to a TreeSet ? Yes, if we use CSO
6. Can I add duplicate Keys to the HashMap ? Yes, Either by Overriding hashCode() or by Overriding equals()
7. How int array class name starts with [. These symbols are not allowed for naming right ?
8. JVM cannot assign default value for local variables. But can assign default values for arrays created locally. Why ?
9. byte b = 1+2 (Correct), byte b = a+1; (Incorrect) ?
10. Object is not parent for interfaces
11. Bytecode verifier verifies before or after loading
12. Sandbox and bytecode verifier
13. print hello in 1 line ( JShell)
14. BIG MYSTERY ..... ??? Clearly written in Paper
interface Interf {
    default void abcC(){ System.out.println("Interface"); }
}
class C{
    //void abcC(){ System.out.println("Class"); }
}
class Test extends C implements Interf {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Test t = new Test();
            t.abcC();
            // C c = new C();
            // c.abcC();
        }
}
Doubt : 15. Comparator(I) contains two abstract methods still it is functional Interface. How ? 
@FunctionalInterface
public interface Comparator<T> {
    int compare(T var1, T var2);
    boolean equals(Object var1);
    .
    .
    .
    .
    .
    }
16. If equals methods is overridden in Comparator interface though the method is already a part of java.lang.object. then why is the default int hashCode() is  not allowed in the Functional interface or any interface ?
17. Is it possible to use new keyword with an Interface ? Yes, as Anonymous Inner Class
18. Create Your own Iterator with Anonymous Inner class and using Diamond Operator
19. Case studies with Var inheritance
20. Can we access private members of one class in another class directly ? Yes. field.setAccessible(true);
21. what is the use of interface containing object class methods as abstract methods in it ? Anyhow interface is going to used by some classes but all classess in java already has Object class Methods through Inheritance.
Ans : Even though Object methods exist in all classes, interfaces can redeclare them to enforce specific contracts. 
interface Identifiable {
    boolean equals(Object obj); // redeclared
    int hashCode();              // redeclared
}
If a class implements Identifiable, the compiler forces you to explicitly provide these methods (unless it’s already overridden in a superclass). This ensures consistent logic for identity and hashing in all implementing classes. Think of it like a reminder note in the interface saying : “Yes, equals exists, but in my world, it must behave this way.”
22. records can't extend any other class becoz by default it is child of Record. Then it is indirect child of Object ?
23. How come local records be static ?1. getClass() gives the runtime Object created but when I use getclass with HashSet reference it is giving HashSet but not HashMap ?
class Testtt{
    // Testtt(){
    //     new Myclass1();
    // }
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception{
        Testtt t = (Testtt)new Myclass1();
        Class c = Class.forName("Testtt");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}
class Myclass1 extends Testtt{
}
